<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,674,1779]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,319,710,735]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Forewing length 
<quantity box="[522,645,710,734]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.85" metricValueMax="4.9" metricValueMin="4.8" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="48.5" valueMax="49.0" valueMin="48.0">48–49 mm</quantity>
in males and 
<quantity box="[808,930,710,734]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" metricValueMax="5.1" metricValueMin="4.9" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="50.0" valueMax="51.0" valueMin="49.0">49–51 mm</quantity>
in females. 
<taxonomicName box="[1072,1219,710,735]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Philaethria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygmalion">
<emphasis box="[1072,1219,710,735]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">P. pygmalion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily separated from the other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[446,573,747,771]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Philaethria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[446,573,747,771]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Philaethria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the dark brown inner postdiscal band on the ventral surface of the hind wing, similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[347,487,782,807]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Metamorpha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wernickei">
<emphasis box="[347,487,782,807]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">P. wernickei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but with the bone white medial postdiscal band very reduced. HW submarginal cellular spots diffuse and continuous. FW postmedial area reduced in size (larger in 
<emphasis box="[1138,1274,819,843]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">P. w e r ni c ke i</emphasis>
). Postmedial, medial and discal area on the ventral surface of both wings light green in coloration. Subapical spot on FW small and reduced in size.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
